'''Lewis Friedman''' is an American screenwriter and speechwriter.  A two-time Emmy nominee, he has written for television and film since 1998.  His credits include the films ''[[The Comedian (2016 film)|The Comedian]]'', ''[[BASEketball]]'' and ''[[An American Carol]]'', the ''Music in High Places'' documentary series, and television specials such as the ''[[Kennedy Center Honors]].''<ref name="emmy">{{cite web|title=Lewis Friedman|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/lewis-friedman|website=emmys.com|publisher=Emmy Awards|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edgington|first1=K.|title=Encyclopedia of Sports Films|date=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3xBVtMpDYaoC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=lewis+friedman+baseketball&source=bl&ots=eWlb7tJvr0&sig=CZl7VrMXSEGrZ2i-n_OBpqBHQi4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDzr7Vrc7QAhXnzVQKHUjMB1MQ6AEIXjAQ#v=onepage&q=lewis%20friedman%20baseketball&f=false|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810876538|page=35|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="IMDb">{{cite web|title=Lewis Friedman|url=http://im.dmim.ir/name/nm0295281/?ref_=tt_ov_wr|website=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>

Friedman was born in New York City and grew up in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, where he attended [[Shorewood High School (Wisconsin)|Shorewood High School]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni by Class|url=http://shorewoodhighschool.org/shorewood-wi/alumni-by-class.html|website=shorewood.com|publisher=Shorewood High School|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> He began his career in Milwaukee in 1972 as a promoter, and later moved to New York, where he promoted Broadway shows such as ''Stories by Chapin'', ''Comedy with Music'' and ''The Middle of Nowhere.''<ref name="nyt">{{cite news|last1=Holden|first1=Stephen|title=The Stage - Stories By Chapin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/30/theater/the-stage-stories-by-chapin.html|accessdate=29 November 2016|work=New York Times|date=April 30, 1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=Nels|title=RANDY NEWMAN'S PLAY IS OPENING HERE, BUT ... HE'S NOWHERE IN SIGHT|work=Philadelphia Daily News|date=October 17, 1989|page=41}}</ref><ref name="DMN">{{cite news|last1=Weeks|first1=Jerome|title=The Middle of Nowhere Stops at Theater 3|work=Dallas Morning News|date=February 24, 1989|page=24}}</ref><ref name="salt lake">{{cite news|last1=Melch|first1=Nancy|title=From Cheech & Chong to `Chicago'; Ballard didn't make Milwaukee famous, but succeeds in bringing quality theater productions to Utah|work=Salt Lake Tribune|date=September 6, 1998|page=D5}}</ref>

Friedman's film screenplays are comedies. His television scripts have focused on the performing arts, and include awards shows such as the Kennedy Center Honors, the [[Golden Globes]], and the [[Directors Guild Awards]].  In addition to the 22 episodes of ''Music in High Places,'' which featured artists such as [[India.Arie]], [[Ryan Adams]], and [[Alanis Morissette]], he has written documentaries about [[Bob Marley]] and [[Burt Bacharach]].<ref name="IMDb" />

He was nominated for two Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for his work on the 2010 and 2012 ''The Kennedy Center Honors: A Celebration of the Performing Arts'' specials. He was nominated for a Writers Guild Award in 2012 and 2016.<ref name="emmy" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Lewis Friedman|url=http://awards.wga.org/search?keywords=Lewis%20Friedman|website=wga.org|publisher=Writers Guild|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>

